At this point expectation calculation is simple, but here I add another
attribute to the puzzle. I want 6 tosses of the 6 dices.<br>
<br>
<span style="font-style: italic; color: rgb(51, 51, 153);">In each set
I will take the minimum value as in the previous part. I will then take
the maximum of these 6 minimum values. Now what is the expectation of
this maximum value?</span><br
 style="font-style: italic; color: rgb(51, 51, 153);">
<span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 255); font-style: italic;">So another
layer is added, and this can be continued for many times, but let's
think of the second layer as of now. </span><br
 style="color: rgb(51, 51, 255);">
<br>
P(X=1) will simply be getting a 1 in all the minimums otherwise it
won't get selected so it's easiest = 0.665102^6 = 0.0865.<br>
P(X=2) is not so simple, and can't be calculated by P(X&gt;2) logic,
since it's a maximum I use P(X&lt;=2) and this time I use the
probabilities calculated previously. <br>
<br>
P(X&lt;=2) = SUM(P(X=1) + P(X=2))^6<br>
Again this includes the case of P(X=1), so I subtract NOT 0.6651, but
0.0865 (calculated above)<br>
so P(X=2) (in this max case) becomes 0.48962<br>
<br>
<small>Similarly P(X=3) becomes SUM(P(X=1) + P(X=2) +
P(X=3)^6&nbsp;&nbsp; - 0.48962 - 0.0865<br>
and we again have the following table<br>
